We have published the Röhm letters under the title *Der Fall Röhm* (The Röhm Affair), distributing the pamphlet across all corners of Germany. This has damaged the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> Party’s appeal among its more socially reactionary supporters and has even sparked a plot among some <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> members to murder Röhm.

The pamphlet argues that a party tolerating homosexuality at its highest levels must seek to "poison the people and destroy its moral strength." It warns that this would lead to Germany’s decline, akin to the fall of ancient Rome, and claims that by keeping Röhm in power, the Nazis are complicit in "knowingly and intentionally furthering the seduction of German youths into becoming homosexual minions."

Despite this, Hitler has swiftly come to Röhm’s defense, publicly reaffirming his position as leader of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**SA**</span>. The electoral performance of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> remains largely unaffected, but the impression this controversy leaves on President Hindenburg may yet prove significant.

Meanwhile, the pamphlet’s publisher, Helmuth Klotz, has been brutally beaten by <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> deputies inside the Reichstag building as an act of revenge—an event that has overshadowed the scandal itself.

